{
  "Normal blood pressure is approximately:": "",
  "140/90 mmHg": "",
  "160/100 mmHg": "",
  "120/80 mmHg": "",
  "90/50 mmHg": "",
  "Normal blood pressure is approximately 120 mmHg systolic (during ventricular contraction) over 80 mmHg diastolic (during ventricular relaxation), which represents the optimal range for healthy adults.": "",
  "Systolic pressure measures the pressure during:": "",
  "Sleep": "",
  "Atrial filling only": "",
  "Ventricular contraction": "",
  "Ventricular relaxation": "",
  "Systolic pressure is the peak arterial pressure generated when the left ventricle contracts and ejects blood into the aorta, representing the highest pressure point in the cardiac cycle.": "",
  "Baroreceptors detect:": "",
  "Changes in blood pressure through stretch of vessel walls": "",
  "Blood oxygen saturation levels via peripheral chemoreceptors": "",
  "Core body temperature via hypothalamic thermoreceptors": "",
  "Blood glucose concentration via pancreatic islet sensors": "",
  "Baroreceptors are specialized pressure-sensing nerve endings located in the carotid sinuses and aortic arch that detect stretching of vessel walls, providing rapid feedback to the brainstem for blood pressure regulation.": "",
  "The RAAS system is activated by:": "",
  "Low blood pressure, causing the kidneys to release renin": "",
  "High blood glucose triggering insulin release from the pancreas": "",
  "High blood pressure causing the kidneys to excrete sodium": "",
  "High calcium levels triggering calcitonin from the thyroid": "",
  "When blood pressure drops, the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidneys detect reduced renal perfusion and release renin, initiating the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone cascade that ultimately raises blood pressure.": "",
  "Angiotensin II causes:": "",
  "Increased urination and lower blood volume": "",
  "Decreased heart rate": "",
  "Potent vasoconstriction and stimulates aldosterone release, increasing blood pressure": "",
  "Vasodilation and decreased blood pressure": "",
  "Angiotensin II is one of the body's most powerful vasoconstrictors; it directly narrows blood vessels and stimulates the adrenal cortex to release aldosterone, which promotes sodium and water retention by the kidneys to increase blood volume.": "",
  "Aldosterone increases blood pressure by:": "",
  "Dilating blood vessels": "",
  "Decreasing heart rate": "",
  "Reducing blood volume through increased urination": "",
  "Causing kidneys to retain sodium and water, increasing blood volume": "",
  "Aldosterone is a mineralocorticoid hormone that acts on the kidney tubules to increase sodium reabsorption; water follows sodium by osmosis, expanding blood volume and thereby raising blood pressure.": "",
  "ADH (vasopressin) increases blood pressure by:": "",
  "Stimulating red blood cell production": "",
  "Causing kidneys to retain water, increasing blood volume": "",
  "Increasing urine output": "",
  "Antidiuretic hormone (ADH/vasopressin) is released from the posterior pituitary in response to dehydration or low blood volume, making the kidney collecting ducts more permeable to water so more water is reabsorbed and blood volume increases.": "",
  "Hypertension is defined as blood pressure consistently at or above:": "",
  "130/80 mmHg": "",
  "100/60 mmHg": "",
  "According to current clinical guidelines, hypertension is defined as blood pressure consistently at or above 130/80 mmHg, with stage 1 hypertension being 130-139/80-89 mmHg and stage 2 being 140/90 mmHg or higher.": "",
  "ANP (atrial natriuretic peptide) is released when:": "",
  "Blood pressure is low, triggering renal renin release and sympathetic activation to restore pressure": "",
  "Dehydration occurs, triggering ADH release from the posterior pituitary to increase water reabsorption": "",
  "Heart rate drops below 60 bpm, triggering sympathetic stimulation of the SA node to increase contractile frequency": "",
  "Atria are stretched by high blood volume, promoting sodium and water excretion to lower BP": "",
  "When blood volume is high, the atrial walls are stretched, triggering release of ANP, which opposes the RAAS by promoting sodium and water excretion in the kidneys and causing vasodilation, thereby lowering blood pressure.": "",
  "Risk factors for hypertension include:": "",
  "Only excessive exercise beyond the body's cardiovascular capacity to adapt": "",
  "Only advanced age and the accompanying decline in vascular elasticity": "",
  "Obesity, high sodium diet, sedentary lifestyle, smoking, genetics, and stress": "",
  "Only inherited genetic polymorphisms affecting renal sodium handling": "",
  "Hypertension is a multifactorial condition influenced by both modifiable factors (diet, exercise, weight, smoking, alcohol, stress) and non-modifiable factors (age, genetics, race), making comprehensive lifestyle modification essential for prevention.": "",
  "What is diastolic pressure?": "",
  "The average pressure throughout the cardiac cycle": "",
  "The peak pressure during ventricular contraction": "",
  "The minimum arterial pressure during ventricular relaxation, reflecting the resting pressure in the arteries": "",
  "The pressure in the veins returning to the heart": "",
  "Diastolic pressure represents the lowest pressure in the arteries when the ventricles are relaxed and refilling; it reflects the baseline resistance and elasticity of the arterial walls between heartbeats.": "",
  "What is mean arterial pressure (MAP)?": "",
  "The simple average of systolic and diastolic pressure calculated by adding both values and dividing by two, used as a quick clinical approximation of perfusion pressure": "",
  "The pressure measured only in the pulmonary arteries during right heart catheterization, used to assess right ventricular function and pulmonary vascular resistance": "",
  "The average driving pressure throughout the cardiac cycle, calculated as diastolic + 1/3(systolic - diastolic), which must stay above ~60 mmHg for organ perfusion": "",
  "The maximum arterial pressure achieved during peak exercise stress testing, used to evaluate cardiovascular fitness and detect exercise-induced ischemia": "",
  "MAP represents the average arterial pressure during one complete cardiac cycle, weighted toward diastole because the heart spends more time in diastole; it must remain above approximately 60 mmHg to adequately perfuse vital organs.": "",
  "What is orthostatic hypotension?": "",
  "Normal blood pressure changes during sleep": "",
  "A sudden drop in blood pressure when standing up, caused by gravity pooling blood in the legs": "",
  "High blood pressure caused by kidney disease": "",
  "Chronically high blood pressure that does not respond to medication": "",
  "Orthostatic hypotension is a drop of at least 20 mmHg systolic or 10 mmHg diastolic within 3 minutes of standing; gravity causes blood to pool in the lower extremities, and if compensatory mechanisms fail, cerebral perfusion drops causing dizziness or fainting.": "",
  "What does 'hypertension is the silent killer' mean?": "",
  "Hypertension often has no symptoms until it causes serious organ damage to the heart, brain, kidneys, or eyes": "",
  "Hypertension always causes immediate, severe symptoms": "",
  "Hypertension only affects people who are asleep": "",
  "Hypertension is harmless and rarely causes complications": "",
  "Hypertension is called the 'silent killer' because it typically produces no noticeable symptoms for years while silently damaging blood vessels and organs, leading to heart attack, stroke, kidney failure, and vision loss if left untreated.": "",
  "What is an ACE inhibitor?": "",
  "A drug that increases sodium retention to maintain blood volume": "",
  "A drug that blocks the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II, causing vasodilation and lowering blood pressure": "",
  "A drug that increases heart rate to improve cardiac output": "",
  "A drug that increases angiotensin II production to raise blood pressure": "",
  "ACE (angiotensin-converting enzyme) inhibitors block the enzyme that converts angiotensin I to the potent vasoconstrictor angiotensin II, resulting in vasodilation, reduced aldosterone secretion, and lower blood pressure.": "",
  "What is hypotension?": "",
  "Temporary high blood pressure during exercise": "",
  "Normal blood pressure variation during sleep": "",
  "Abnormally low blood pressure that can cause dizziness, fainting, and inadequate organ perfusion": "",
  "Blood pressure that is consistently elevated above 130/80 mmHg": "",
  "Hypotension occurs when blood pressure is too low to adequately perfuse organs, potentially causing dizziness, fainting (syncope), confusion, and in severe cases, shock with organ failure due to insufficient blood flow.": "",
  "What does RAAS stand for?": "",
  "Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System": "",
  "Renal Artery Activation System": "",
  "Renal Antidiuretic Adrenal System": "",
  "Rapid Arterial Assessment Scale": "",
  "The Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System is a hormonal cascade involving the kidneys, liver, lungs, and adrenal glands that works to increase blood pressure through vasoconstriction and sodium/water retention when pressure is detected as low.": "",
  "What does the DASH diet mean in the context of hypertension management?": "",
  "A high-sodium, high-fat diet recommended for athletes": "",
  "A diet that eliminates all carbohydrates": "",
  "Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension - a low-sodium diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and low-fat dairy": "",
  "A fasting protocol for rapid weight loss": "",
  "The DASH diet is an evidence-based dietary plan specifically designed to reduce blood pressure through reduced sodium intake and emphasis on potassium-rich fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and low-fat dairy products.": "",
  "What is syncope?": "",
  "Rapid heart rate exceeding 150 beats per minute, known as supraventricular tachycardia, caused by an abnormal electrical circuit": "",
  "Temporary loss of consciousness (fainting) caused by insufficient blood flow to the brain": "",
  "Chronic high blood pressure exceeding 140/90 mmHg, known as hypertension, caused by increased vascular resistance": "",
  "Chest pain occurring during physical exercise, known as angina pectoris, caused by reduced coronary blood flow to the myocardium": "",
  "Syncope is a transient loss of consciousness and postural tone due to reduced cerebral blood flow, often caused by hypotension, and typically resolves quickly once the person is in a recumbent position and blood flow to the brain is restored.": "",
  "What does 'baroreceptor reflex' mean?": "",
  "A conscious decision to regulate blood pressure": "",
  "A hormonal response that takes hours to affect blood pressure": "",
  "A rapid, automatic neural mechanism that adjusts heart rate and vessel tone in response to detected changes in blood pressure": "",
  "A mechanism that only works during exercise": "",
  "The baroreceptor reflex is a rapid negative feedback loop where baroreceptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch detect pressure changes and signal the medulla oblongata to adjust sympathetic and parasympathetic output, modifying heart rate and vessel diameter within seconds.": "",
  "A 55-year-old patient with no symptoms has a blood pressure reading of 155/95 mmHg on three separate visits. The physician explains that untreated hypertension can damage multiple organs. Which organs are most at risk from chronic hypertension?": "",
  "Only the stomach and intestines": "",
  "Only the skin and muscles": "",
  "Only the lungs and liver": "",
  "The heart, brain, kidneys, and eyes (retina)": "",
  "Chronic hypertension causes end-organ damage to the heart (hypertrophy, heart failure), brain (stroke), kidneys (nephrosclerosis, renal failure), and eyes (hypertensive retinopathy), making it a leading risk factor for cardiovascular morbidity and mortality.": "",
  "An elderly patient on blood pressure medication stands up quickly from bed and feels extremely dizzy, nearly fainting. The nurse checks blood pressure lying down (140/85) and standing (95/60). What is this condition and why did it occur?": "",
  "Dehydration from not drinking enough water": "",
  "Hypertensive crisis; the medication raised blood pressure too high": "",
  "A heart attack caused by standing too quickly": "",
  "Orthostatic hypotension; the blood pressure medication and age impaired the body's ability to compensate for gravity-induced blood pooling when standing": "",
  "Antihypertensive medications can impair the baroreceptor reflex and reduce the compensatory vasoconstriction needed when standing; combined with age-related blunting of baroreceptors, this causes a significant BP drop upon standing, reducing cerebral perfusion.": "",
  "A patient with chronic kidney disease develops hypertension that is difficult to control with medication. The nephrologist explains that the kidneys are directly contributing to the high blood pressure. What mechanism links kidney disease to hypertension?": "",
  "Damaged kidneys produce too much ANP, raising blood pressure": "",
  "Kidney disease causes the heart to beat faster": "",
  "Kidney disease destroys baroreceptors in the aorta": "",
  "Damaged kidneys cannot excrete sodium and water properly and may overactivate the RAAS, increasing blood volume and vasoconstriction": "",
  "Diseased kidneys lose their ability to properly excrete sodium and water, leading to fluid retention and volume expansion; additionally, reduced renal perfusion can inappropriately activate the RAAS, causing further vasoconstriction and salt/water retention in a vicious cycle.": "",
  "A patient with heart failure is prescribed an ACE inhibitor and a diuretic. The physician explains these medications address different mechanisms. How does each medication lower blood pressure?": "",
  "The ACE inhibitor reduces vasoconstriction by blocking angiotensin II formation, while the diuretic reduces blood volume by promoting sodium and water excretion": "",
  "Both increase aldosterone to help the kidneys filter more blood": "",
  "The ACE inhibitor increases heart rate while the diuretic decreases blood viscosity": "",
  "Both work by slowing heart rate through the vagus nerve": "",
  "ACE inhibitors lower BP by preventing formation of angiotensin II (reducing vasoconstriction and aldosterone), while diuretics directly promote renal excretion of sodium and water, reducing blood volume; together they address both vascular resistance and fluid overload.": "",
  "During a blood donation, a donor suddenly feels lightheaded, nauseous, and their blood pressure drops to 85/55 mmHg. The nurse tilts the chair back and elevates the donor's legs. Why does this maneuver help?": "",
  "Elevating the legs uses gravity to return pooled venous blood to the heart, increasing preload and cardiac output to restore blood pressure": "",
  "It activates the sympathetic nervous system through muscle contraction": "",
  "It reduces the heart rate to conserve energy": "",
  "It stimulates the donor to breathe faster": "",
  "The Trendelenburg position (legs elevated) uses gravity to shift blood from the lower extremities back toward the central circulation, increasing venous return (preload) to the heart, which increases stroke volume via the Frank-Starling mechanism and helps restore blood pressure.": "",
  "A hypertensive patient asks why reducing sodium in their diet helps lower blood pressure. Which physiological mechanism explains the relationship between sodium and blood pressure?": "",
  "Sodium increases heart rate": "",
  "Sodium directly constricts arteries": "",
  "Excess sodium causes water retention by osmosis, increasing blood volume and therefore blood pressure": "",
  "Sodium thickens the blood by increasing red blood cell production": "",
  "When excess sodium is present in the blood, water follows by osmosis to maintain osmotic balance, increasing total blood volume; greater blood volume means more blood is pumped with each cardiac cycle, raising pressure against arterial walls.": "",
  "A patient in the ICU has a MAP of 50 mmHg. The critical care team is urgently administering IV fluids and vasopressors. Why is a MAP below 60 mmHg a medical emergency?": "",
  "A low MAP only affects the lungs": "",
  "A MAP below 60 mmHg is insufficient to perfuse vital organs like the brain and kidneys, leading to organ failure and death": "",
  "A low MAP causes excessive urination leading to dehydration": "",
  "A low MAP causes blood to clot too quickly": "",
  "Mean arterial pressure must remain above approximately 60 mmHg to maintain adequate blood flow to vital organs; below this threshold, organs become ischemic, and prolonged hypoperfusion leads to cellular death, organ failure, and potentially death.": "",
  "A pregnant woman in her third trimester develops a blood pressure of 165/110 mmHg, protein in her urine, and severe headaches. The obstetrician diagnoses preeclampsia. Why is this condition dangerous for both mother and baby?": "",
  "Severely elevated BP can damage the mother's organs (liver, kidneys, brain) and restrict blood flow to the placenta, compromising fetal development": "",
  "It only affects blood sugar levels": "",
  "It increases fetal heart rate but has no effect on the mother": "",
  "It only causes mild discomfort that resolves after delivery": "",
  "Preeclampsia involves severe hypertension and endothelial dysfunction that can damage the mother's kidneys, liver, and brain (potentially progressing to eclampsia with seizures), while restricted placental blood flow can cause fetal growth restriction and premature birth.": "",
  "A 45-year-old man with untreated hypertension suffers a hemorrhagic stroke. His physician explains that the high blood pressure contributed directly to the stroke. How does chronic hypertension lead to hemorrhagic stroke?": "",
  "High blood pressure dissolves clots that normally protect vessel walls": "",
  "Hypertension causes the brain to swell, compressing blood vessels": "",
  "Chronic high pressure weakens and damages small cerebral arteries, which can eventually rupture and bleed into the brain": "",
  "Hypertension causes blood to become too thin, leading to spontaneous bleeding": "",
  "Years of elevated blood pressure weaken the walls of small cerebral arteries through a process called lipohyalinosis, forming microaneurysms that can rupture under continued high pressure, causing intracerebral hemorrhage and potentially devastating neurological damage.": "",
  "A patient taking a beta-blocker for hypertension asks why the medication makes their heart rate slower. How do beta-blockers reduce blood pressure?": "",
  "They increase renin release from the kidneys": "",
  "They directly relax smooth muscle in the arteries by blocking calcium channels": "",
  "They block the parasympathetic nervous system, causing vasodilation": "",
  "They block beta-adrenergic receptors, reducing heart rate and contractility, which lowers cardiac output and blood pressure": "",
  "Beta-blockers block the effects of epinephrine and norepinephrine on beta-1 adrenergic receptors in the heart, reducing heart rate (negative chronotropy) and contractile force (negative inotropy), which decreases cardiac output and lowers blood pressure.": ""
